  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Bank Secrecy Act\n- Strict reporting requirements\n- Aggressive prosecution\n- Focus on financial institution compliance\n- Significant criminal and civil penalties\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified anti-money laundering directives\n- Centralized regulatory framework\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Emphasis on transparency\n- Collaborative cross-border enforcement\n\n3. Switzerland\n- Traditionally strict banking secrecy laws\n- Gradually increasing transparency\n- Sophisticated compliance mechanisms\n- Strong financial regulation\n- Cooperation with international investigations\n\n4. United Kingdom\n- Robust regulatory environment\n- Sophisticated financial crime legislation\n- Advanced suspicious transaction reporting\n- Significant focus on beneficial ownership\n- Proactive international cooperation\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict capital controls\n- Increasing international compliance\n- Growing emphasis on financial transparency\n- State-controlled enforcement mechanisms\n\n6. Russia\n- Complex legal framework\n- Inconsistent enforcement\n- Significant underground economic activities\n- Developing regulatory infrastructure\n- Limited international cooperation\n\nThese approaches reflect diverse legal, cultural, and economic contexts in addressing money laundering risks.",
